properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory for today through Friday. Flurries and local snow squalls are expected to develop off Georgian Bay and Lake Huron this morning. These flurries and snow squalls are then expected to continue intermittently through Friday afternoon. While the heaviest snow squalls are expected to remain south and east of the Bruce Peninsula, portions of the Peninsula can expect locally heavy snow and reduced visibilities at times making travel difficult. Motorists are advised to watch for quickly changing weather conditions and adjust their driving accordingly. Locally heavy snowfall accumulations of 5 to 15 cm will be possible. If the snow squalls look to be more intense or persistent than currently forecast, a Snow Squall Warning may be required for the area. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow Squalls expected Thursday into Friday. Snow squalls are expected to develop off Georgian Bay and Lake Huron late Thursday morning and continue through Friday afternoon. The squalls will become more organized and intensify as the winds shift to the north Thursday afternoon. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A Pacific front will move onto Peace River region early on Friday morning. This will be followed by an Arctic front pushing through the region in the afternoon and then stalling on Saturday. Long period of snow at times mixed with rain is expected with 20 to 40 cm total accumulation possible by Saturday afternoon. Snow will begin over Williston region and Pine pass today then change to rain or mixed with rain tonight as the warm Pacific front approaches. Rain mixed with snow is expected to develop overnight over southern Peace River region then change to snow Friday when the Arctic front pushes through. Northern Peace River region will likely stay north of the warm front and receive highest amount of snowfall. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Rain or wet snow for the Islands Thursday night, followed by colder temperatures, flurries and strong winds for Friday and Saturday. A weather system will bring rain to the Islands beginning late in the day Thursday, then change to wet snow overnight. Flurries will develop on Friday as colder air and stronger winds move into the region from the northwest. Saturday will be an unseasonably cold and blustery day with frequent flurries that could give a few centimetres of accumulation.
